## Key concepts to master

### Population concepts

| Concept | What to know |
|---|---|
| **Population density** | Arithmetic, physiological, and agricultural density — three different ways to measure it |
| **Population distribution** | Where people live and why (climate, water, jobs, history) |
| **Crude birth rate (CBR)** | Births per 1,000 people per year |
| **Crude death rate (CDR)** | Deaths per 1,000 people per year |
| **Natural increase rate (NIR)** | (CBR − CDR) ÷ 10, expressed as a percentage |
| **Total fertility rate (TFR)** | Average number of children per woman; 2.1 = replacement level |
| **Doubling time** | Years for a population to double — calculated as 70 ÷ NIR(%) |
| **Dependency ratio** | Ratio of dependents (under 15 + over 64) to working-age population |

### Population models

- **Demographic Transition Model (DTM)** — 5 stages from high birth/death rates to low birth/death rates
- **Epidemiologic Transition Model** — how causes of death change as countries develop
- **Malthusian theory** — population grows faster than food supply (predicts crisis)
- **Boserup theory** — population growth drives agricultural innovation (counters Malthus)
- **Demographic momentum** — population keeps growing even after fertility drops, due to young population structure

### Migration concepts

| Concept | What to know |
|---|---|
| **Push factors** | What forces people to leave (war, drought, unemployment) |
| **Pull factors** | What attracts people to a destination (jobs, safety, family) |
| **Intervening obstacles** | Barriers that block or redirect migration |
| **Intervening opportunities** | Reasons people stop short of their original destination |
| **Step migration** | Moving in stages (village → small city → big city) |
| **Chain migration** | Moving to where family or community has already settled |
| **Forced migration** | Slavery, refugees, internally displaced persons (IDPs) |
| **Voluntary migration** | Economic, social, environmental, political (not forced) |
| **Refugees vs asylum seekers vs IDPs** | Refugees cross borders; asylum seekers request status; IDPs stay within country |

### Ravenstein's Laws of Migration

Most migrants move short distances, in steps, toward economic centers. Long-distance migrants usually go to major cities. Most migration is rural to urban. Each migration stream produces a counter-stream. Young adults migrate more than families.

