## Frequently asked

**How much of the AP exam is Unit 2?**
Unit 2 is one of the highest-weight units, making up about 12–17% of multiple-choice questions. It's also one of the most common FRQ topics — at least one FRQ usually involves population or migration.

**Do I need to memorize the demographic transition model stages?**
Yes. You should know all 5 stages, the birth and death rate trends in each, example countries, and what triggers movement between stages. The DTM is one of the most-tested concepts in AP HUG.

**Is replacement-level fertility 2.0 or 2.1?**
Replacement level is **2.1** — 2 children to replace the parents, plus 0.1 to account for child mortality and people who don't have children. In countries with very low child mortality, the number is closer to 2.0.

**What's the difference between crude birth rate and total fertility rate?**
Crude birth rate (CBR) is births per 1,000 people in the total population per year. Total fertility rate (TFR) is the average number of children one woman would have over her lifetime. CBR depends on age structure; TFR doesn't.

**How do I tell push factors from pull factors?**
Push factors are negative — they push people out of a place (war, famine, persecution). Pull factors are positive — they pull people toward a destination (jobs, safety, education, family). Most migration involves both.

